2.ğŸ”„ Understanding Special Types in TypeScript: any, unknown, and never

TypeScript introduces advanced types like any, unknown, and never to handle different levels of type flexibility and safety. Hereâ€™s how they work and when to use them effectively:
________________________________________
ğŸ”“ any: Maximum Flexibility, Minimum Safety
The any type disables type checking for a variable. It accepts any kind of value and allows all operationsâ€”whether valid or notâ€”without compiler complaints. While it's convenient, overuse can introduce silent bugs that appear only at runtime.
âœ… Characteristics:
1.	Accepts any data type (string, number, object, etc.)
2.	Can be used directly without restrictions
3.	Bypasses TypeScriptâ€™s type checking system
4.	âŒ Unsafe for dynamic or unknown inputs
let flexibleVar: any = 10;
flexibleVar = "hello";
flexibleVar.someMethod(); // âœ… Compiles, âŒ Runtime error if someMethod doesn't exist

unknown: Type-Safe Flexibility
The unknown type is similar to any in that it can store any valueâ€”but with one crucial difference: you cannot use it directly until you validate its type. This forces safer coding practices when handling uncertain data (e.g., user inputs, API responses).
âœ… Characteristics:
1.	Accepts any type of value
2.	âŒ Cannot be used directly without type checks
3.	âœ… Safe for handling dynamic data
4.	Encourages use of type guards or type assertions
let unknownVar: unknown = 42;
// unknownVar.toFixed(2); // âŒ Compile-time error
  
if (typeof unknownVar === 'number') {
  unknownVar.toFixed(2); // âœ… Safe to use after type check
}
never: Represents the Impossible
The never type represents values that should never exist. It is typically used in:
â€¢	Functions that always throw errors
â€¢	Infinite loops
â€¢	Exhaustive checks in switch/case statements to ensure no case is missed
âœ… Characteristics:
1.	Accepts no values at all
2.	âŒ Cannot be used directly
3.	âœ… Safe for control flow logic to handle unreachable code

function throwError(message: string): never {
  throw new Error(message); // Function never returns
}

function infiniteLoop(): never {
  while (true) {} // Runs forever, never ends
}
Example: Exhaustiveness Check
type Shape = 'circle' | 'square';

function getArea(shape: Shape) {
  switch (shape) {
    case 'circle': return Math.PI * 1 * 1;
    case 'square': return 1 * 1;
    default:
      const _exhaustiveCheck: never = shape; // Ensures all cases are handled
      return _exhaustiveCheck;
  }
}

